# Breaking Down if/else Statements

What do if/else if/else statements actually do? They let you control the flow of your program. 

## What is an if statement?

<br/>
<img src="https://images.code.org/d62a7b736e7d69957b1c129e0a4ecbe0-image-1437086155945.png" width="300" style="float: left; padding-right: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;"></img>


When your computer sees the keyword **if**, (represented by a diamond in these images), it knows it has reached a point where it needs to branch off and decide whether or not to execute a piece of code. How does it decide? Well, it checks the **condition** you put *inside* your if statement. It looks between the parentheses and checks whether your condition is **true** or **false**.

<code style="color: black"><purple>if</purple> (<blue>condition</blue>) { <orange>body</orange>; } </code>

If the condition is true, you computer will read the following section of code and execute the **body** of the if statement. If the condition is false, your computer will treat the body of the if statement *as if it didn't exist*. It skips it entirely! 

<br/>
This kind of condition, that can only be evaluated to true or false is called a **Boolean** condition.


<details>
<summary>What's with that funny word *Boolean*?</summary>
George Boole was a mathematician who was born in England in the mid 1800s who laid the foundation for Boolean algebra. Boolean algebra is a form of algebra in which the variables represent the values are *true* and *false* rather than the numbers 0-9.
</details>

## What happens with an if/else statement?


<img src="https://images.code.org/7f9d457746e3e92324a8e0863aa6088d-image-1437086176386.png" width="400" style="float: right; padding-left: 20px; padding-bottom: 20px;"></img>

Just like the word "if," "else" is a keyword that your computer reads. If your computer reads an **if** that evaluates to **false**, it will check if the keyword **else** shows up directly after the closed curly brace "**}**". If it sees an **else**, it will know it needs to take a default action.

<code style="color: black"><purple>if</purple> (<blue>condition</blue>) {</code><br/>
<code>	&nbsp;&nbsp;<orange>body of if</orange> ;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>} <purple>else</purple> { &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>&nbsp;&nbsp;<orange>body of else</orange>; </code><br/>
<code>} &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code>

<br/>
If the **condition** evaluates to **true**, the computer will treat the body of the "else" as if it didn't exist. If the **condition** evaluates to **false**, the computer will treat the body of the "if" as if it didn't exist. It will only take one of the two possible paths.

## What about an if/else if/else?

<img src="https://images.code.org/588c6bc9181a591ac20f22d7539b6336-image-1437086182350.png" width="300" style="float: left; padding-right: 20px;"></img>

<br/>

Once again, the computer chooses only one of the possible paths. When the computer sees the "else" keyword, it will check if there is an "if" following it. If there is an "if", the computer will then follow the same logic as it does with a normal "if" statement. 

<code style="color: black"><purple>if</purple> (<blue>condition</blue>) { &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>	&nbsp;&nbsp;<orange>body of if</orange>; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>} <purple>else if</purple> (<blue>condition</blue>) {</code><br/>
<code> &nbsp;&nbsp;<orange>body of else if</orange>; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>} <purple>else</purple> { &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>&nbsp;&nbsp;<orange>body of else</orange>;  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code><br/>
<code>} &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</code>

If the condition evaluates to **true**, the computer will execute the body of the **else if** statement and ignore everything else. If the condition evaluates to **false**, the computer will check for the next **else** statement.
